Section Header: INTRODUCTION
Field Label: A1. Hello.  We are conducting a voluntary study for which you may be eligible.  The study will follow a group of pregnant women to see if they get COVID-19 and will help us to learn more about the impact of COVID-19 on pregnant women.  This study will involve being contacted once a week by text message or email (or by telephone if needed) while you are pregnant to answer a few brief screening questions. You will also be asked to collect respiratory samples from your nose and mail them to a central laboratory once a week in a pre-paid package. If you get sick, we will ask you to collect an additional respiratory sample with each illness episode and mail it to the central laboratory in a pre-paid package. You will also be asked to have blood drawn around the time you enroll in the study, up to one additional time during the study, and within 2-4 weeks of the end of your pregnancy. Study staff will also contact you monthly throughout your pregnancy and once after you have your baby to ask you questions about your health and your pregnancy and delivery.  May I talk to you about this study and ask you a few short questions to see if you are eligible to participate?

Section Header: INTRODUCCIÓN
Field Label: A1. Hola. Estamos haciendo un estudio voluntario para el que usted puede ser elegible. El estudio seguirá a un grupo de mujeres embarazadas para ver si contraen COVID-19 y nos ayudará a conocer más sobre el impacto del COVID-19 en las mujeres embarazadas. Este estudio implicará ser contactada una vez a la semana por medio de mensaje de texto o correo electrónico (o por teléfono si es necesario) durante el embarazo para responder algunas preguntas breves de detección. También se le pedirá que tome muestras respiratorias de su nariz y las envíe por correo a un laboratorio central, una vez a la semana, en un paquete prepago. Si se enferma, le pediremos que tome una muestra respiratoria adicional con cada episodio de la enfermedad y la envíe por correo al laboratorio central, en un paquete prepago. También se le pedirá que permita la extracción de sangre al momento en que se inscriba en el estudio, una vez más durante el estudio y dentro de las 2-4 semanas después del final de su embarazo. El personal del estudio también se comunicará con usted mensualmente durante su embarazo y cuando tenga a su bebé para hacerle preguntas sobre su salud y su embarazo y parto. ¿Puedo hablar con usted sobre este estudio y hacerle algunas preguntas breves para ver si es elegible para participar?

Section Header: 1. What you should know about this study (Key Information):
Field Label:
You are being asked to be in a research study conducted by Columbia University Irving Medical Center. Â This study is being done to help understand the rate of infection and effects during pregnancy from SARS-CoV-2, the virus that causes COVID-19. Â If you decide to join this study,

  1. You will be asked to fill out surveys about your health and collect weekly respiratory samples for testing for SARS-CoV-2, the virus that causes COVID-19. Â Respiratory samples could include a swab placed in your nose and/or mouth.
  2. You will also be asked to have blood drawn around the time you enroll in the study, up to one additional time during the study, and within 2-4 weeks of the end of your pregnancy.Â 
  3. You will be asked to allow us access to your health record at Columbia University Irving Medical Center.Â 
  4. This study is expected to last for two years. If you choose to take part in this study, we will ask you to remain in the study until approximately 2-4 weeks after the end of your pregnancy. Â Â 
  5. The most common risk of joining is mild discomfort associated with self-collection of respiratory samples and minor pain with blood draws when the needle is inserted, very occasionally fainting, and some possible bruising afterward.Â 
  6. We will do everything we can to protect your privacy. But there is still a very small chance that an unauthorized person could access your information.Â 
  7. You will not directly benefit from this study. You are also contributing to help researchers understand the risks of SARS-CoV-2 infection and the progress of the illness.Â 
  8. Being in this study is completely voluntary. Â You can withdraw (quit) at any time. The alternative is not to join.Â 

This is a consent form. It tells you important information about a research study to help you decide whether or not you would like to take part in the study. Please read this form carefully before signing. A member of our study team will also talk to you about this study. Â Please read the information below and ask questions about anything you don't understand before deciding whether or not to take part. For you to be in the study, you must provide your consent. We will also give you a copy of this form to keep. Â Â

Section Header: 2. What is this COVID-19?
Field Label: Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) is the name of the illness caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2).  Common COVID-19 symptoms include cough, shortness of breath or difficulty breathing, fever, chills, muscle pain, sore throat, and new loss of taste or smell.  COVID-19 symptoms may range from mild to very severe, and some people may have no signs or symptoms at all.  People of any age who have underlying chronic medical conditions might be at higher risk for severe illness from COVID-19. Changes in the body during pregnancy may put pregnant women at greater risk of some severe respiratory infections.

Section Header: 3. Why is this study being done?
Field Label:
We are inviting pregnant woman and their infants to be in a research study to learn more about COVID-19. The purpose of this study is to learn the following:

  • How many pregnant woman get sick with COVID-19
  • What symptoms are common if pregnant women have COVID-19
  • How long it takes to recover from COVID-19
  • How many pregnant women become infected with SARS-CoV-2 but do not become sick
  • If there are any associated complications during pregnancy and after birth if a pregnant woman gets sick with COVID-19
  • What are pregnant women's knowledge, attitudes and practices related to COVID-19
  • If and when a COVID-19 vaccine becomes available, how well it protects pregnant women from infection

Section Header: 4. Who is doing this research study?
Field Label: The study is being done by Columbia University Irving Medical Center in collaboration with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and Abt Associates Inc. (referred to as Abt Associates). Different healthcare centers and universities across the United States will help with this CDC-funded study.

Section Header: 5. Do I have to be in this research study?
Field Label: No, being in this study is completely voluntary, meaning you can choose whether or not you want to be a part of it. If you choose not to take part in the study, it will not affect your job/employment or the care you receive at Columbia University Irving Medical Center or at any other medical provider. Even if you do take part in the study, you can quit at any time.

Section Header: 6. Who will take part in this study?
Field Label: Up to approximately 500 pregnant woman in Columbia University Irving Medical Center will participate in this study.  Up to 3,000 pregnant women across the country age 18 and over will be asked to take part in this study.

Section Header: 7. What will I be asked to do if I take part in this study?
Field Label:
This study is expected to last for two years. If you choose to take part in this study, we will ask you to remain in the study until approximately 2-4 weeks after the end of your pregnancy. We will also ask you to do these steps:

Planned Surveys: Enrollment and End of Study
When you enroll, we will ask you questions about yourself, your work, and your mental health, substance use, medical history, pregnancy history, prenatal history, seasonal flu vaccination status, and knowledge related to COVID-19. A survey will also be given 2-4 weeks after the end of your pregnancy to collect information on your social history, pregnancy, hospital experience, and vaccines during pregnancy. You will be able to complete these surveys online through a link we send to you, or by phone or virtual interview with a study staff person. Answers are entered into a secure electronic database. You may refuse to answer any survey or survey question you don't want to answer and you may end the survey at any time. If we do not receive your survey, we will follow-up by phone. Your answers to survey questions will be kept private.

Designate a Proxy
During the enrollment process, we will ask if you are able to designate a partner, family member, or friend to serve as a proxy. You may choose to designate more than one proxy if you want. If study staff are unable to reach you during the study, they will contact your designated proxy to find out how you are doing and whether you have been diagnosed with COVID-19. Your proxy will also be asked to contact us at the time that you go into labor or your pregnancy ends, if you are not able to contact us yourself. You do not have to designate a proxy to be able to participate in this study.

Weekly Checks for COVID-19 Symptoms
Once per week, we will send you a text message to ask if you have developed any symptoms that may be related to COVID-19. You will be reminded to call study staff or send a text message if you develop illness symptoms, go into labor or experience end of pregnancy. We will follow-up by phone if we are unable to get a reply.

Nasal Swab Sample Collection
Once a week, on the same day as the symptom reporting outlined above, we will ask you to collect respiratory sample(s) from yourself and send the sample(s) to a CDC-designated laboratory. We ask that you collect samples even if you do not have any symptoms. We will ask you to collect additional respiratory sample(s) if you develop specific symptoms associated with COVID-19. Respiratory samples could include a swab placed in your nose and/or mouth. The test materials and instructions to collect samples will be given to you when you join the study. The laboratory will test the samples to find out if you have COVID-19 or other respiratory infections like influenza. This COVID-19 test is in addition to any tests that your medical provider may order as part of your medical care. The test results will only be shared with you and not with your medical provider. Test results may also be shared with public health authorities per local and state COVID-19 reporting guidelines. Please note that sample results may not be immediately available. Therefore, the testing conducted for this study should not be used to decide whether you seek medical care or to make decisions about whether or not you should stay home and/or separate yourself from others. If you feel ill at any time during the study, you should consult with your medical provider. Although you will receive results from the testing of your respiratory samples, results will not be available for a week or more after you ship your respiratory sample to the study lab. Although the molecular tests for COVID-19 used in this study are highly accurate, they are not perfect. It is unlikely, but a negative test result can occur even if you are infected. In addition, a negative test result will not tell you if you have been infected in the days since you collected your sample.

Blood Samples
We will collect a 20 ml, about 4 teaspoons, blood sample from you at the beginning of the study. If you are at < 24 weeks into your pregnancy right now, we will also collect a blood sample when you reach 26 to 30 weeks into your pregnancy and again around the end of your pregnancy or up to 4 weeks after your pregnancy ends. This will tell us if you had SARS-CoV-2 infection during your pregnancy, even if you had no symptoms. We will schedule a time for you to come to Columbia University Irving Medical Center to collect the blood samples.

Illness Surveys
If you become sick with COVID-19 symptoms during the study, we will contact you to respond online or by telephone to questions about your illness. In a weekly text message, we will ask if you still have symptoms. Once your symptoms end or about 4 weeks after you reported your illness to the study team (whichever happens first), we will send you a link to an online survey with questions about how your illness went. We will follow-up by phone if we are unable to get a reply to the online survey. Answers are entered into a secure electronic database. You may refuse to answer any question you don't want to answer and you may end any of the surveys at any time. Your answers to survey questions will be kept completely private.

Medical Records
Study staff will look at your relevant medical records and the medical record of your baby once he/she is born at Columbia University Irving Medical Center to learn more about your health, your medical history, pregnancy history, and medical visits that may be related to COVID-19 during the study period. Examples include: diagnosed pregnancy complications, delivery outcomes, infant complications, hospitalizations, duration of hospital stay after birth, doctor visits for respiratory illnesses, treatment you received, vaccines, medications you may be taking, and your infant's medical record (including delivery outcomes and complications such as diagnoses, clinical course, and the duration of hospital stay after birth). We will enter the information into a secure computer database.

Vaccine Verification
If you receive the influenza vaccine during your pregnancy or if a COVID-19 vaccine becomes available and you receive it, we will ask for the name(s) and location(s) of the care provider(s) who gave you the vaccine(s). If you were vaccinated at Columbia University Irving Medical Center or one of our clinics, we will look into our records to confirm your vaccination status.

If the vaccine is not given within our health system, we may check state and/or city vaccine registries or talk to your primary care doctor to confirm your vaccination status. If you received the vaccine at a pharmacy, grocery store, or other business, we may contact that company and ask them to verify your vaccination.

Section Header: 8. What are the possible risks of this study?
Field Label:
Collecting a nasal swab may cause very minor discomfort. Getting blood drawn may cause minor pain when the needle is inserted, very occasionally fainting, and some possible bruising afterward.

Although all information on you, your health, the samples you provide, and testing results will be kept in a secured data base, there is a risk that an unauthorized person could get access to this data. We believe the chance this will happen is very small and we will do everything we can to protect your privacy.

There may also be other risks that we currently don't know about.

Section Header: 9. What are the possible benefits of this study?
Field Label: You will not directly benefit from this study. Your participation in this study will teach us a lot about COVID-19 and SARS-CoV-2.  If so, that could benefit you, or someone you know, in the future.

Section Header: 10. How will my confidentiality and personal health information be protected?
Field Label:
Columbia University Irving Medical Center is committed to protecting your personal health information (like your name, medical history and date of birth) and the risk of disclosure is minimal.

To protect your confidentiality, we will use a number instead of your name on all forms and we will store your data in password protected files located on secure computers. If information from this study is shown publicly or published in a journal, you will not be mentioned by name, picture, or in any other way that could identify you.

This is a combined consent and HIPAA authorization. By taking part in this study, you grant permission for the researchers in this study to look at you and your infant(s) personal health information and to disclose it to our research partners (Abt Associates, CDC, and participating healthcare centers and universities across the United States) for the purposes of lab testing, data analysis, and preparing articles for publication, as well as to review boards and other persons who watch over the safety, effectiveness, and conduct of research such as authorized representatives of the Office of Human Research Protections ("OHRP"), and Columbia University Irving Medical Center Institutional Review Board. The investigator, regulatory authorities, IRB and study sponsor may keep the research records indefinitely. We will not disclose any information that could identify you or your infant, such as your name, contact information, or health record number.

This research will be covered by a Certificate of Confidentiality from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. The researchers with this Certificate may not disclose or use information, documents, or biospecimens that may identify you in any federal, state, or local civil, criminal, administrative, legislative, or other action, suit, or proceeding, or be used as evidence, for example, if there is a court subpoena, unless you have consented for this use. Information, documents, or biospecimens protected by this Certificate cannot be disclosed to anyone else who is not connected with the research except, if there is a federal, state, or local law that requires disclosure (such as to report child abuse or communicable diseases but not for federal, state, or local civil, criminal, administrative, legislative, or other proceedings, see below); if you have consented to the disclosure, including for your medical treatment; or if it is used for other scientific research, as allowed by federal regulations protecting research subjects.

The Certificate cannot be used to refuse a request for information from personnel of the United States federal or state government agency sponsoring the project that is needed for auditing or program evaluation by the SPONSOR which is funding this project. You should understand that a Certificate of Confidentiality does not prevent you from voluntarily releasing information about yourself or your involvement in this research. If you want your research information released to an insurer, medical provider, or any other person not connected with the research, you must provide consent to allow the researchers to release it.

The Certificate of Confidentiality will not be used to prevent disclosure as required by federal, state, or local law due to harm to yourself or others.

The Certificate of Confidentiality will not be used to prevent disclosure for any purpose you have consented to in this informed consent document.

Section Header: 11. Are there any costs for being in the study?
Field Label: There is no cost to you or your insurance for taking part in this study. You may incur charges from your cell phone service provider for message/data rates that apply to messages sent for this study.

Section Header: 12. Will I receive any payment for being in the study?
Field Label: Each participant will receive a Bank of America refillable visa card and payment will be as followed:  $20 for enrollment, $10 a week to defray the costs of the required texts/emails/phone calls and for the weekly nasal swab, $10 for each package sent and $15 for completing post-partum survey, and $25 for each blood draw.

Section Header: 13. How will my respiratory samples be used for this study?
Field Label: Your respiratory samples will be sent to a CDC-designated lab to find out if you have been infected with SARS-CoV-2.  If your sample confirms SARS-CoV-2 infection, we may do more tests on your sample.  Please note, this test is not meant to take the place of any tests that your medical provider may order as part of your medical care. The results from the research test will not affect your medical care.  The test results will be shared with you and the research study staff.  We will follow your institution's rules and guidelines for reporting COVID-19 test results. We may also be required to report your results, name, and contact information to your local public health authority.

Section Header: 14. How will my blood samples be used for this study?
Field Label: Your blood samples will be sent to CDC-designated research labs and will be tested for proteins in the blood called antibodies to determine whether you were infected with SARS-CoV-2 and how well your immune system responds if you were infected. The test results will be shared with you and study investigators, but are for research purposes and may not be available for a long time.

Section Header: 15. How will my samples be used in the future?
Field Label: If there are leftover samples that the researchers do not need for this study, we plan to store them for future testing for other respiratory infections and for testing to evaluate the body's immune response to respiratory infections.  Samples may be stored at CDC or a CDC-designated sample storage facility and may be tested by CDC or other CDC-designated investigators. Your research samples may also be shared with other research institutions to test for other respiratory infections and evaluate the body's immune response to respiratory infections.  If we do, we will not include any information that could identify you.

Section Header: 16. Can I withdraw from the study?
Field Label: Yes, you are free to withdraw your consent or stop being a part of this study at any time.  The decision will not affect in any way your current or future medical care or your employment.  The study staff may stop you from taking part in this study if they decide it is in your best interest or if you do not follow study instructions.  If you withdraw from the study, data and samples that were already collected may still be used for this study.

Section Header: 17. If I have questions or concerns about this research study, who can I call?
Field Label: If you have more questions about the study, you may speak to Melissa Stockwell, MD, MPH at Columbia University Irving Medical Center. If you have questions about your rights as a participant in this research study or think you have been harmed, please contact the Institutional Review Board at Columbia University +1212-305-5883 or email (irboffice@columbia.edu) or visit the website at http://www.cumc.columbia.edu/ dept/irb/info.html. An IRB is a group that protects the rights and welfare of human subjects involved in research and mention that you are calling about the Epidemiology of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 in Pregnancy and Infancy (ESPI) Network Community Cohort Study.

Section Header: Consentimiento para Participar en Estudio Médico
Field Label:
Título del Estudio: Epidemiología del Síndrome Respiratorio Agudo Severo del Coronavirus 2 en Grupo Comunitario de la Red de Estudios Sobre Embarazo e Infancia (ESPI, siglas en inglés)          
                                                          Investigadora Principal: Melissa S. Stockwell (mss2112)
Co-Investigadora: Cynthia Gyamfi Bannerman (cg2231)
Dirección: 622 W 168th Street
New York, NY 10032
Teléfono: 212-342-5732

Section Header: 1. Lo que usted debe saber sobre este estudio (Información clave):
Field Label:
A usted se le pide que participe en un estudio de investigación realizado por el Centro Médico Irving de la Universidad de Columbia. Este estudio se está realizando para ayudar a comprender la tasa de infección y los efectos durante el embarazo del SARS-CoV-2, el virus que causa COVID-19. Si decide participar en este estudio,

  1. Se le pedirá que complete encuestas sobre su salud y recolecte muestras respiratorias semanales para analizar el SARS-CoV-2, el virus que causa COVID-19.  Las muestras respiratorias podrían incluir un hisopo colocado en su nariz y/o boca.
  2. También se le pedirá que permita que se le extraiga sangre en el momento en que se inscriba en el estudio, hasta una vez más durante el estudio y dentro de las 2 o 4 semanas después del final de su embarazo.
  3. Se le pedirá que nos permita acceder a su archivo de salud en el Centro Médico Irving de la Universidad de Columbia.
  4. Se espera que este estudio dure dos años. Si elige participar en este estudio, le pediremos que permanezca en el estudio hasta aproximadamente 2-4 semanas después del final de su embarazo.
  5. El riesgo más común de participar es una leve molestia asociada con la recolección de las muestras respiratorias y un dolor leve con la extracción de la sangre cuando se inserta la aguja, muy ocasionalmente desmayos y algunos posibles hematomas después de éstas.
  6. Haremos todo lo posible para proteger su privacidad. Pero aún así hay una pequeña posibilidad de que una persona no autorizada pueda acceder a su información.
  7. Usted no se beneficiará directamente de este estudio. Usted también está contribuyendo a ayudar a los investigadores a comprender los riesgos de la infección por SARS-CoV-2 y el progreso de la enfermedad.
  8. Participar en este estudio es completamente voluntario. Puede retirarse (salir) en cualquier momento. La alternativa es no participar.

Este es un formulario de consentimiento. El mismo le ofrece información importante sobre un estudio de investigación para ayudarle a decidir si desea o no participar en el estudio. Lea este formulario detenidamente antes de firmarlo. Un miembro de nuestro equipo del estudio también le hablará sobre este estudio. Lea la información a continuación y haga preguntas sobre cualquier cosa que no entienda antes de decidir si participa o no. Para que pueda participar en el estudio, debe proporcionar su consentimiento. También le daremos una copia de este formulario para que la guarde.

Section Header: 2. ¿Qué es COVID-19?
Field Label: La enfermedad por coronavirus 2019 (COVID-19) es el nombre de la enfermedad causada por el síndrome respiratorio agudo severo del coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2). Los síntomas comunes de COVID-19 incluyen tos, la falta de aire o dificultad para respirar, fiebre, escalofríos, dolor muscular, dolor de garganta y nueva pérdida de sabor u olfato. Los síntomas de COVID-19 pueden variar de leves a muy severos, y algunas personas pueden no tener señales o síntomas. Las personas de cualquier edad que tienen afecciones médicas crónicas subyacentes pueden estar en mayor riesgo de enfermedad grave por COVID-19. Los cambios en el cuerpo durante el embarazo pueden poner a las mujeres embarazadas en mayor riesgo de algunas infecciones respiratorias severas.

Section Header: 3. ¿Por qué se está haciendo este estudio?
Field Label:
Invitamos a las mujeres embarazadas y sus bebés a participar en un estudio de investigación para obtener más información sobre COVID-19. El propósito de este estudio es aprender lo siguiente:.

  • Cuántas mujeres embarazadas se enferman con COVID-19
  • Qué síntomas son comunes si las mujeres embarazadas tienen COVID-19
  • Cuánto tiempo se toma recuperarse de COVID-19
  • Cuántas mujeres embarazadas se infectan con el SARS-CoV-2 pero no se enferman
  • Si una mujer embarazada se enferma con COVID-19, si hay alguna complicación asociada durante el embarazo y después del parto
  • Cuáles son los conocimientos, actitudes y prácticas de las mujeres embarazadas relacionadas con COVID-19
  • Si y cuando una vacuna COVID-19 esté disponible, qué tan bien protege a las mujeres embarazadas de la infección

Section Header: 4. ¿Quién está realizando este estudio de investigación?
Field Label: El estudio está siendo realizado por el Centro Médico Irving de la Universidad de Columbia en colaboración con los Centros para el Control y la Prevención de Enfermedades (CDC) y Abt Associates Inc. (a quienes nos referimos como Abt Associates). Diferentes centros de salud y universidades de los Estados Unidos ayudarán con este estudio financiado por los CDC.

Section Header: 5. ¿Tengo yo que participar en este estudio de investigación?
Field Label: No, participar en este estudio es completamente voluntario, lo que significa que usted puede elegir si desea o no ser parte de él. Si elige no participar en el estudio, no afectará su trabajo/empleo o la atención que recibe en el Centro Médico Irving de la Universidad de Columbia o en cualquier otro proveedor médico. Incluso si participa en el estudio, puede renunciar (retirarse) en cualquier momento.

Section Header: 6.¿Quién va a participar en este estudio?
Field Label: Aproximadamente 500 mujeres embarazadas en el Centro Médico Irving de la Universidad de Columbia participarán en este estudio. Se les pedirá a hasta tres mil mujeres embarazadas en todo el país, de 18 años o más, que participen en este estudio.

Section Header: 7. ¿Qué se me pedirá que haga si decido participar en este estudio?
Field Label:
Se espera que este estudio dure dos años. Si elige participar en este estudio, le pediremos que permanezca en el estudio hasta aproximadamente 2 o 4 semanas después del final de su embarazo. También le pediremos que haga los siguientes pasos:

Encuestas Planificadas: Al Inscribirse y al Final del Estudio
Cuando se inscriba, le haremos preguntas sobre usted, su trabajo y su salud mental, uso de sustancias, historial médico, historial de embarazo, historial prenatal, estado de vacunación contra el flu estacional y conocimientos relacionados con COVID-19. También se hará una encuesta de 2 a 4 semanas después del final de su embarazo para recopilar información sobre su historial social, embarazo, experiencia hospitalaria y vacunas durante el embarazo. Podrá completar estas encuestas en línea a través de un enlace que le enviamos, o por teléfono o entrevista virtual con un miembro del personal del estudio. Las respuestas se ingresan en una base de datos electrónica segura. Usted puede negarse a responder cualquier encuesta o pregunta de la encuesta que no desee responder y puede finalizar la encuesta en cualquier momento. Si no recibimos su encuesta, haremos un seguimiento por teléfono. Sus respuestas a las preguntas de la encuesta se mantendrán en privado.

Designar un Apoderado(a)
Durante el proceso de inscripción, le preguntaremos si puede designar a un(a) compañero(a), familiar o amigo para que actúe como apoderado(a) o representante. Puede elegir designar más de un(a) apoderado(a) si lo desea. Si el personal del estudio no puede comunicarse con usted durante el estudio, se comunicará con su apoderado(a) designado para averiguar cómo le está yendo y si le han diagnosticado COVID-19. También se le pedirá a su apoderado(a) que se comunique con nosotros en el momento en que entre en labor de parto o finalice su embarazo, si usted no puede comunicarse con nosotros. No tiene que designar un(a) apoderado(a) para poder participar en este estudio.

Verificaciones Semanales de Síntomas de COVID-19
Una vez por semana, le enviaremos un mensaje de texto para preguntarle si ha desarrollado algún síntoma que pueda estar relacionado con COVID-19. Se le recordará que llame al personal del estudio o que envíe un mensaje de texto si desarrolla síntomas de enfermedad, entra en labor de parto o experimenta el final del embarazo. Haremos un seguimiento por teléfono si no podemos obtener una respuesta.

Recolección de Muestras de Hisopos Nasales
Una vez a la semana, el mismo día del informe de síntomas descrito anteriormente, le pediremos que recolecte muestras respiratorias de usted misma y las envíe a un laboratorio designado por los CDC. Le pedimos que recolecte las muestras incluso si no tiene ningún síntoma. Le pediremos que recolecte muestras respiratorias adicionales si desarrolla síntomas específicos asociados con COVID-19. Las muestras respiratorias podrían incluir un hisopo colocado en su nariz y/o boca. Los materiales de prueba y las instrucciones para recolectar las muestras se le entregarán cuando se inscriba en el estudio. El laboratorio analizará las muestras para determinar si tiene COVID-19 u otras infecciones respiratorias como la influenza. Esta prueba de COVID-19 es adicional a cualquier prueba que su proveedor médico pueda ordenar como parte de su atención médica. Compartiremos con usted si su prueba es positiva. Los resultados de la prueba sólo se compartirán con usted y no con su proveedor médico. Los resultados de las pruebas también se pueden compartir con las autoridades de salud pública según las reglas locales y estatales de informes de COVID-19. Tenga en cuenta que los resultados de la muestra pueden no estar disponibles de inmediato. Por lo tanto, las pruebas realizadas para este estudio no deben usarse para decidir si busca atención médica o para tomar decisiones sobre si debe quedarse en casa y/o aislarse de los demás. Si se siente enferma en cualquier momento durante el estudio, debe consultar con su proveedor médico. Aunque usted recibirá resultados positivos de las pruebas de sus muestras respiratorias, los resultados no estarán disponibles durante al menos una semana o más después de enviar su muestra respiratoria al laboratorio del estudio. Aunque las pruebas moleculares para COVID-19 utilizadas en este estudio son muy precisas, no son perfectas. Es poco probable, pero puede ocurrir un resultado negativo, incluso si está infectada. Además, la prueba no le dirá si se ha estado infectada en los días después de la recolección de su muestra.

Muestras de Sangre
Tomaremos una muestra de sangre de 20 ml, aproximadamente 4 cucharaditas, al comienzo del estudio. Si tiene menos de 24 semanas de embarazo en ese momento, también tomaremos una muestra de sangre cuando llegue de 26 a 30 semanas de embarazo y nuevamente al final de su embarazo o hasta 4 semanas después de que termine su embarazo. Recibirá resultados individuales de análisis de sangre. Estos resultados nos dirán si tuvo infección por SARS-CoV-2 durante su embarazo, incluso si no tuvo síntomas. Los resultados de la prueba solo se compartirán con usted y no con su proveedor médico. Tenga en cuenta que los resultados de la muestra pueden no estar disponibles de inmediato. Programaremos un horario para que usted venga al Centro Médico Irving de la Universidad de Columbia para tomar las muestras de sangre.

Encuestas de Enfermedad
Si se enferma con los síntomas de COVID-19 durante el estudio, nos comunicaremos con usted para que responda en línea o por teléfono a preguntas sobre su enfermedad. En un mensaje de texto semanal, le preguntaremos si aún tiene síntomas. Una vez que sus síntomas desaparezcan o aproximadamente 4 semanas después de haber informado sobre su enfermedad al equipo de estudio (lo que ocurra primero), le enviaremos un enlace para una encuesta en línea con preguntas sobre cómo fue su enfermedad. Haremos un seguimiento por teléfono si no podemos obtener una respuesta a la encuesta en línea. Las respuestas se ingresan en una base de datos electrónica segura. Puede negarse a responder cualquier pregunta que no desee responder y puede finalizar cualquiera de las encuestas en cualquier momento. Sus respuestas a las preguntas de la encuesta se mantendrán completamente en privado.

Archivos Médicos
El personal del estudio examinará sus archivos médicos relevantes y el archivo médico de su bebé una vez que él/ella nazca en el Centro Médico Irving de la Universidad de Columbia para obtener más información sobre su salud, su historial médico, historial de embarazo y visitas médicas que pueden estar relacionadas con COVID-19 durante el período del estudio. Los ejemplos incluyen: complicaciones diagnosticadas del embarazo, resultados del parto, complicaciones infantiles, hospitalizaciones, duración de la estadía en el hospital después del nacimiento, visitas al médico por enfermedades respiratorias, tratamiento que recibió, vacunas, medicamentos que puede estar tomando y el historial médico de su bebé (incluyendo los resultados del parto y complicaciones tales como diagnósticos, curso clínico y la duración de la hospitalización después del nacimiento). Ingresaremos la información en una base de datos informática segura.

Verificación de Vacuna
Si recibe la vacuna contra la influenza durante su embarazo o si una vacuna de COVID-19 está disponible y la recibe, le pediremos los nombres y la ubicación de los proveedores de atención médica que le administraron la(s) vacuna(s). Si fue vacunada en el Centro Médico Irving de la Universidad de Columbia o en una de nuestras clínicas, revisaremos nuestros registros para confirmar su estado de vacunación.
Si la vacuna no se administra dentro de nuestro sistema de salud, podemos verificar los registros de vacunas estatales y/o municipales o hablar con su médico de atención primaria para confirmar su estado de vacunación. Si recibió la vacuna en una farmacia, supermercado u otro negocio, podemos comunicarnos con esa compañía y pedirles que verifiquen su vacuna.

Section Header: 8. ¿Cuáles son los posibles riesgos de este estudio?
Field Label:
Obtener una muestra con un hisopo nasal puede causar molestias muy leves. La extracción de sangre puede causar un dolor leve cuando se inserta la aguja, muy ocasionalmente desmayos y algunos posibles moretones después del proceso.

Si bien toda la información sobre usted, su salud, las muestras que proporcione y los resultados de las pruebas se mantendrán en una base de datos segura, existe el riesgo de que una persona no autorizada pueda acceder a estos datos. Creemos que la posibilidad de que esto suceda es muy pequeña y haremos todo lo posible para proteger su privacidad.

También puede haber otros riesgos que actualmente no conocemos.

Section Header: 9. ¿Cuáles son los posibles beneficios de este estudio?
Field Label: Usted no se beneficiará directamente de este estudio. Su participación en este estudio nos enseñará mucho sobre COVID-19 y SARS-CoV-2. Si es así, eso podría beneficiarle a usted o a alguien que usted conoce, en el futuro.

Section Header: 10. ¿Cómo se protegerá mi confidencialidad y mi información personal de salud?
Field Label:
El Centro Médico Irving de la Universidad de Columbia se compromete a proteger su información médica personal (tales como su nombre, historial médico y fecha de nacimiento) y el riesgo de divulgación es mínimo.

Para proteger su confidencialidad, utilizaremos un número en lugar de su nombre en todos los formularios y almacenaremos sus datos en archivos protegidos con contraseña ubicados en computadoras seguras. Si la información de este estudio se muestra públicamente o se publica en una revista, a usted no se le mencionará por nombre ni imagen ni de cualquier otra manera que pueda identificarle.

Este es un consentimiento combinado con una autorización HIPAA. Al participar en este estudio, usted otorga permiso a los investigadores en este estudio para ver su información personal de salud y la de su(s) bebé(s) y divulgarla a nuestros socios del estudio de investigación (Abt Associates, los CDC y los centros de salud y universidades participantes, en todo los Estados Unidos) para fines de pruebas de laboratorio, análisis de datos y preparación de artículos para su publicación, así como para juntas de revisión y otras personas que velan por la seguridad, la eficacia y la realización de investigaciones, tales como los representantes autorizados de la Oficina de Protección de Humanos que Participan en Estudios de Investigación ("OHRP", siglas en inglés) y Junta de Revisión Institucional del Centro Médico Irving de la Universidad de Columbia. La investigadora, las autoridades reguladoras, la junta de revisión institucional y el patrocinador del estudio pueden guardar los registros de la investigación indefinidamente. No divulgaremos ninguna información que pueda identificarle a usted o a su bebé, tal como su nombre, información de contacto o número de registro médico.

Este estudio estará cubierto por un Certificado de Confidencialidad de los Centros para el Control y la Prevención de Enfermedades. Los investigadores con este Certificado no pueden divulgar ni utilizar información, documentos o bioespecificaciones que puedan identificarle en ninguna acción, demanda o procedimiento civil, penal, administrativo, legislativo u otro procedimiento federal, estatal o local, o ser utilizado como evidencia, por ejemplo, si hay una citación judicial, a menos que usted haya dado su consentimiento para este uso. La información, los documentos o las muestras biológicas protegidas por este Certificado no se pueden divulgar a ninguna otra persona que no esté relacionada con la investigación, excepto si existe una ley federal, estatal o local que requiera su divulgación (tal como informar abuso infantil o enfermedades transmisibles, pero no para procedimientos civiles, penales, administrativos, legislativos u otros procedimientos federales, estatales o locales, ver más abajo); si ha dado su consentimiento para la divulgación, incluyendo para su tratamiento médico; o si se usa para otra investigación científica, según lo permitido por las regulaciones federales que protegen a los sujetos de investigación.

El Certificado no se puede utilizar para rechazar una solicitud de información del personal de la agencia del gobierno federal o estatal de los Estados Unidos que patrocina el proyecto que se necesita para la auditoría o evaluación del programa por parte del PATROCINADOR que financia este proyecto. Usted debe comprender que un Certificado de Confidencialidad no le impide a usted divulgar voluntariamente información sobre usted o su participación en esta investigación. Si desea que su información de la investigación se divulgue a una aseguradora, proveedor médico o cualquier otra persona que no esté relacionada con la investigación, debe dar su consentimiento para permitir que los investigadores la liberen.

El Certificado de Confidencialidad no se utilizará para evitar la divulgación según lo requieren las leyes federales, estatales o locales debido a daños a usted o a otros.

El Certificado de Confidencialidad no se utilizará para evitar la divulgación para ningún propósito que usted haya consentido en este documento de consentimiento informado.

Section Header: 11.¿Hay algún costo por participar en el estudio?
Field Label: No hay ningún costo para usted o su seguro por participar en este estudio. Es posible que su proveedor de servicios de teléfono celular le cobre por los mensajes/uso de data que apliquen por los mensajes enviados para este estudio.

Section Header: 12. ¿Recibiré algún pago por participar en el estudio?
Field Label: Cada participante recibirá una tarjeta Visa recargable del Bank of America y el pago será de la siguiente manera: $20 por inscripción, $10 por semana para cubrir los costos de los mensajes de texto/correos electrónicos/llamadas telefónicas requeridas y por el hisopo nasal semanal, $10 por cada paquete enviado y $15 por completar la encuesta posparto, y $25 por cada extracción de sangre.

Section Header: 13. ¿Cómo se usarán mis muestras respiratorias para este estudio?
Field Label: Sus muestras respiratorias se enviarán a un laboratorio designado por los CDC para averiguar si ha sido infectada con SARS-CoV-2. Si su muestra confirma la infección por SARS-CoV-2, podemos hacer más pruebas en sus muestras. Tenga en cuenta que esta prueba no está destinada a reemplazar cualquier prueba que su proveedor médico pueda ordenar como parte de su atención médica. Los resultados de la prueba del estudio no afectarán su atención médica. Los resultados de la prueba se compartirán con usted y el personal del estudio de investigación. Seguiremos las reglas y pautas de su institución para informar los resultados de la prueba COVID-19. También es posible que tengamos que informar sus resultados, nombre e información de contacto a su autoridad local de salud pública.

Section Header: 14. ¿Cómo se usarán mis muestras de sangre para este estudio?
Field Label: Sus muestras de sangre se enviarán a los laboratorios de investigación designados por los CDC y se analizarán las proteínas en la sangre llamadas anticuerpos para determinar si estaba infectada con el SARS-CoV-2 y qué tan bien responde su sistema inmunitario si estaba infectada. Los resultados de la prueba se compartirán con usted y los investigadores del estudio, pero son para fines de investigación y es posible que no estén disponibles durante mucho tiempo.

Section Header: 15. ¿Cómo se usarán mis muestras en el futuro?
Field Label: Si hay restos de muestras que los investigadores no necesiten para este estudio, planeamos almacenarlas para futuras pruebas de otras infecciones respiratorias y para evaluar la respuesta inmune del cuerpo a las infecciones respiratorias. Todos los identificadores serían eliminados y después de dicha eliminación, la información o las bioespecificaciones podrían usarse para futuros estudios de investigación sin consentimiento adicional. Las muestras pueden almacenarse en los CDC o en una instalación de almacenamiento de muestras designada por los CDC y pueden ser analizadas por los CDC u otros investigadores designados por los CDC. Sus muestras de la investigación también se pueden compartir con otras instituciones de investigación para detectar otras infecciones respiratorias y evaluar la respuesta inmune del cuerpo a las infecciones respiratorias. Si lo hacemos, no incluiremos ninguna información que pueda identificarle.

Section Header: 16. ¿Me puedo retirar del estudio?
Field Label: Sí, puede retirar su consentimiento o dejar de participar en este estudio en cualquier momento. La decisión no afectará de ninguna manera su atención médica actual o futura o su empleo. El personal del estudio puede impedir que participe en este estudio si ellos deciden que es lo mejor para usted o si no sigue las instrucciones del estudio. Si se retira del estudio, los datos y las muestras que ya se recopilaron aún pueden usarse para este estudio.

Section Header: 17. Si tengo preguntas o inquietudes sobre este estudio de investigación, ¿a quién puedo llamar?
Field Label: Si tiene más preguntas sobre el estudio, puede hablar con la Dra. Melissa Stockwell, MPH en el Centro Médico Irving de la Universidad de Columbia. Si tiene preguntas sobre sus derechos como participante en este estudio de investigación o cree que se ha visto perjudicada, comuníquese con la Junta de Revisión Institucional (IRB, siglas en inglés) de la Universidad de Columbia al (212) 305-5883 o envíe un correo electrónico (irboffice@columbia.edu) o visite el sitio web en http://www.cumc.columbia.edu/dept/irb/info.html y mencione que está llamando sobre el estudio de Epidemiología del Síndrome Respiratorio Agudo Severo del Coronavirus 2 en Grupo Comunitario de la Red de Estudios Sobre Embarazo e Infancia (ESPI). Un IRB es un grupo que protege los derechos y el bienestar de los sujetos humanos involucrados en un estudio de investigación.

Section Header: Consent to Participate in Medical Research
Field Label:
Study Title: The Epidemiology of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 in Pregnancy and Infancy (ESPI) Network Community Cohort Study

Section Header: 1. What you should know about this study (Key Information):
Field Label:
You are being asked to be in a research study conducted by UAB. This study is being done to help understand the rate of infection and effects during pregnancy from SARS-CoV-2, the virus that causes COVID-19. If you decide to join this study,

  1. You will be asked to fill out surveys about your health and collect weekly respiratory samples for testing for SARS-CoV-2, the virus that causes COVID-19. Respiratory samples could include a swab placed in your nose and/or saliva.
  2. You will also be asked to have blood drawn around the time you enroll in the study, up to one additional time during the study, and within 2-4 weeks of the end of your pregnancy.
  3. You will be asked to allow us access to your health record at UAB.
  4. This study is expected to last for two If you choose to take part in this study, we will ask you to remain in the study until approximately 2-4 weeks after the end of your pregnancy.
  5. The most common risk of joining is mild discomfort associated with self-collection of respiratory samples and minor pain with blood draws when the needle is inserted, very occasionally fainting, and some possible bruising afterward.
  6. We will do everything we can to protect your privacy. But there is still a very small chance that an unauthorized person could access your information.
  7. You may benefit by knowing the results of frequent COVID-19 testing. You are also contributing to help researchers understand the risks of SARS-CoV-2 infection and the progress of the illness.
  8. Being in this study is completely voluntary. You can withdraw (quit) at any time. The alternative is not to join.

This is a consent form. It tells you important information about a research study to help you decide whether or not you would like to take part in the study. Please read this form carefully before signing. A member of our study team will also talk to you about this study. Please read the information below and ask questions about anything you don't understand before deciding whether or not to take part. For you to be in the study, you must provide your consent. We will also give you a copy of this form to keep.

Section Header: 2. What is COVID-19?
Field Label: Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) is the name of the illness caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2). Common COVID-19 symptoms include cough, shortness of breath or difficulty breathing, fever, chills, muscle pain, sore throat, and new loss of taste or smell. COVID-19 symptoms may range from mild to very severe, and some people may have no signs or symptoms at all. People of any age who have underlying chronic medical conditions might be at higher risk for severe illness from COVID-19. Changes in the body during pregnancy may put pregnant women at greater risk of some severe respiratory infections.

Section Header: 3. Why is this study being done?
Field Label:
We are inviting pregnant woman and their infants to be in a research study to learn more about COVID-19. The purpose of this study is to learn the following:

  • How many pregnant woman get sick with COVID-19
  • What symptoms are common if pregnant women have COVID-19
  • How long it takes to recover from COVID-19
  • How many pregnant women become infected with SARS-CoV-2 but do not become sick
  • If there are any associated complications during pregnancy and after birth if a pregnant woman gets sick with COVID-19
  • What are pregnant women's knowledge, attitudes and practices related to COVID-19
  • If and when a COVID-19 vaccine becomes available, how well it protects pregnant women from infection

Section Header: 4. Who is doing this research study?
Field Label: The study is being done by UAB in collaboration with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and Abt Associates Inc. (referred to as Abt Associates). Different healthcare centers and universities across the United States will help with this CDC-funded study.

Section Header: 5. Do I have to be in this research study?
Field Label: No, being in this study is completely voluntary, meaning you can choose whether or not you want to be a part of it. If you choose not to take part in the study, it will not affect your job/employment or the care you receive at UAB or at any other medical provider. Even if you do take part in the study, you can quit at any time.

Section Header: 6. Who will take part in this study?
Field Label: Up to approximately 500 pregnant woman at UAB will participate in this study. Up to 3,000 pregnant women across the country age 18 and over will be asked to take part in this study.

Section Header: 7. What will I be asked to do if I take part in this study?
Field Label:
This study is expected to last for two years. If you choose to take part in this study, we will ask you to remain in the study until approximately 2-4 weeks after the end of your pregnancy. We will also ask you to do these steps:

Planned Surveys: Enrollment and End of Study

When you enroll, we will ask you questions about yourself, your work, and your health, medical history, pregnancy history, prenatal history, seasonal flu vaccination status, and knowledge related to COVID-19. A survey will also be given 2-4 weeks after the end of your pregnancy to collect information on your social history, pregnancy, hospital experience, and vaccines during pregnancy. You will be able to complete these surveys online through a link we send to you, or by phone or virtual interview with a study staff person. Answers are entered into a secure electronic database. You may refuse to answer any survey or survey question you don't want to answer and you may end the survey at any time. If we do not receive your survey, we will follow-up by phone. Your answers to survey questions will be kept private.

Designate a Proxy

During the enrollment process, we will ask if you are able to designate a partner, family member, or friend to serve as a proxy. You may choose to designate more than one proxy if you want. If study staff are unable to reach you during the study, they will contact your designated proxy to find out how you are doing and whether you have been diagnosed with COVID-19. Your proxy will also be asked to contact us at the time that you go into labor or your pregnancy ends, if you are not able to contact us yourself. You do not have to designate a proxy to be able to participate in this study.

Weekly Checks for COVID-19 Symptoms

Once per week, we will send you a text message to ask if you have developed any symptoms that may be related to COVID-19. You will be reminded to call study staff or send a text message if you develop illness symptoms, go into labor or experience end of pregnancy. We will follow-up by phone if we are unable to get a reply.

Nasal Swab Sample Collection

Once a week, on the same day as the symptom reporting outlined above, we will ask you to collect respiratory sample(s) from yourself and send the sample(s) to a CDC-designated laboratory. We ask that you collect samples even if you do not have any symptoms. We will ask you to collect additional respiratory sample(s) if you develop specific symptoms associated with COVID-19. Respiratory samples could include a swab placed in your nose and/or saliva. The test materials and instructions to collect samples will be given to you when you join the study. The laboratory will test the samples to find out if you have COVID-19 or other respiratory infections like influenza. This COVID-19 test is in addition to any tests that your provider may order as part of your medical care. We will share with you if your test is positive. The test results will only be shared with you and not with your medical provider. Test results may also be shared with public health authorities per local and state COVID-19 reporting guidelines. Please note that sample results may not be immediately available. Therefore, the testing conducted for this study should not be used to decide whether you seek medical care or to make decisions about whether or not you should stay home and/or separate yourself from others. If you feel ill at any time during the study, you should consult with your medical care provider. Although you will receive results if positive from the testing of your respiratory samples, results will not be available for a week or more after you ship your respiratory sample to the study lab. Although the molecular tests for COVID-19 used in this study are highly accurate, they are not perfect. It is unlikely, but a negative test result can occur even if you are infected. In addition, the test will not tell you if you have been infected in the days since you collected your sample.

Blood Samples

We will collect a 20 ml, about 4 teaspoons, blood sample from you at the beginning of the study. If you are at < 24 weeks into your pregnancy right now, we will also collect a blood sample when you reach 26 to 30 weeks into your pregnancy and again around the end of your pregnancy or up to 4 weeks after your pregnancy ends. You will receive individual research blood results. These results will tell us if you had SARS-CoV-2 infection during your pregnancy, even if you had no symptoms. The test results will only be shared with you and not with your medical provider. Please note that sample results may not be immediately available. We will schedule a time for you to come to UAB to collect the blood samples.

Illness Surveys

If you become sick with COVID-19 symptoms during the study, we will contact you to respond online or by telephone to questions about your illness. In a weekly text message, we will ask if you still have symptoms. Once your symptoms end or about 4 weeks after you reported your illness to the study team (whichever happens first), we will send you a link to an online survey with questions about how your illness went. We will follow-up by phone if we are unable to get a reply to the online survey. Answers are entered into a secure electronic database. You may refuse to answer any question you don't want to answer and you may end any of the surveys at any time. Your answers to survey questions will be kept completely private.

Medical Records

Study staff will look at your relevant medical records and the medical record of your baby once he/she is born at UAB to learn more about your health, your medical history, pregnancy history, and medical visits that may be related to COVID-19 during the study period. Examples include: diagnosed pregnancy complications, delivery outcomes, infant complications, hospitalizations, duration of hospital stay after birth, doctor visits for respiratory illnesses, treatment you received, vaccines, medications you may be taking, and your infant's medical record (including delivery outcomes and complications such as diagnoses, clinical course, and the duration of hospital stay after birth). We will enter the information into a secure computer database.

Vaccine Verification

If you receive the influenza vaccine during your pregnancy or if a COVID-19 vaccine becomes available and you receive it, we will ask for the name(s) and location(s) of the care provider(s) who gave you the vaccine(s). If you were vaccinated at UAB or one of our clinics, we will look into our records to confirm your vaccination status.

If the vaccine is not given within our health system, we may check state and/or city vaccine registries or talk to your primary care doctor to confirm your vaccination status. If you received the vaccine at a pharmacy, grocery store, or other business, we may contact that company and ask them to verify your vaccination.

Section Header: 8. What are the possible risks of this study?
Field Label:
Collecting a nasal swab may cause very minor discomfort. Getting blood drawn may cause minor pain when the needle is inserted, very occasionally fainting, and some possible bruising afterward.

Although all information on you, your health, the samples you provide, and testing results will be kept in a secured data base, there is a risk that an unauthorized person could get access to this data. We believe the chance this will happen is very small and we will do everything we can to protect your privacy.

There may also be other risks that we currently don't know about.

Section Header: 9. What are the possible benefits of this study?
Field Label: You will not directly benefit from this study. Your participation in this study will teach us a lot about COVID-19 and SARS-CoV-2. If so, that could benefit you, or someone you know, in the future.

Section Header: 10. How will my confidentiality and personal health information be protected?
Field Label:
UAB is committed to protecting your personal health information (like your name, medical history and date of birth) and the risk of disclosure is minimal.

To protect your confidentiality, we will use a number instead of your name on all forms and we will store your data in password protected files located on secure computers. If information from this study is shown publicly or published in a journal, you will not be mentioned by name, picture, or in any other way that could identify you.

This is a combined consent and HIPAA authorization. By taking part in this study, you grant permission for the researchers in this study to look at you and your infant(s) personal health information and to disclose it to our research partners (Abt Associates, CDC, and participating healthcare centers and universities across the United States) for the purposes of lab testing, data analysis, and preparing articles for publication, as well as to review boards and other persons who watch over the safety, effectiveness, and conduct of research such as authorized representatives of the Office of Human Research Protections ("OHRP"), and UAB Institutional Review Board. The investigator, regulatory authorities, IRB and study sponsor may keep the research records indefinitely. We will not disclose any information that could identify you or your infant, such as your name, contact information, or health record number.

Your consent form will be placed in your medical record at UAB Health System. This may include either a paper medical record or electronic medical record (EMR). An EMR is an electronic version of a paper medical record of your care within this health system. Your EMR may indicate that you are on a clinical trial and provide the name and contact information for the principal investigator.

If you are receiving care or have received care within this health system (outpatient or inpatient) and are participating in a research study, results of research tests or procedures (i.e. laboratory tests, imaging studies and clinical procedures) may be placed in your existing medical record.

If you have never received care within this health system (outpatient or inpatient) and are participating in a research study, a medical record will be created for you to maintain results of research tests or procedures.

Results of research tests or procedures may be placed in your medical record. All information within your medical record can be viewed by individuals authorized to access the record.

This research will be covered by a Certificate of Confidentiality from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. The researchers with this Certificate may not disclose or use information, documents, or biospecimens that may identify you in any federal, state, or local civil, criminal, administrative, legislative, or other action, suit, or proceeding, or be used as evidence, for example, if there is a court subpoena, unless you have consented for this use. Information, documents, or biospecimens protected by this Certificate cannot be disclosed to anyone else who is not connected with the research except, if there is a federal, state, or local law that requires disclosure (such as to report child abuse or communicable diseases but not for federal, state, or local civil, criminal, administrative, legislative, or other proceedings, see below); if you have consented to the disclosure, including for your medical treatment; or if it is used for other scientific research, as allowed by federal regulations protecting research subjects.

The Certificate cannot be used to refuse a request for information from personnel of the United States federal or state government agency sponsoring the project that is needed for auditing or program evaluation by the SPONSOR which is funding this project. You should understand that a Certificate of Confidentiality does not prevent you from voluntarily releasing information about yourself or your involvement in this research. If you want your research information released to an insurer, medical care provider, or any other person not connected with the research, you must provide consent to allow the researchers to release it.

The Certificate of Confidentiality will not be used to prevent disclosure as required by federal, state, or local law due to harm to yourself or others.

The Certificate of Confidentiality will not be used to prevent disclosure for any purpose you have consented to in this informed consent document.

Section Header: 11. Are there any costs for being in the study?
Field Label: There is no cost to you or your insurance for taking part in this study. You may incur charges from your cell phone service provider for message/data rates that apply to messages sent for this study.

Section Header: 12. Will I receive any payment for being in the study?
Field Label:
You will be paid the following for your participation in this study:
Enrollment - $50
Weekly swabs - $10 each
Clinic visits after enrollment at which blood is drawn - $20

Section Header: 13. How will my respiratory samples be used for this study?
Field Label: Your respiratory samples will be sent to a CDC-designated lab to find out if you have been infected with SARS- CoV-2. If your sample confirms SARS-CoV-2 infection, we may do more tests on your sample.  Please note, this test is not meant to take the place of any tests that your provider may order as part of your medical care. The results from the research test will not affect your medical care. The test results will be shared with you and the research study staff.  We will follow your institution's rules and guidelines for reporting COVID-19 test results. We may also be required to report your results and contact information to your local public health authority.
